### Component 2 — JS (`userRenderer.js`)

#### [MODIFY] userRenderer.js — Add `renderGroupedUsers()` + update `renderUsersTableData`

- **`renderUsersTableData(users)`** — keep writing to `#users-tbody` (hidden table, no visual change). Additionally call `renderGroupedUsers(adminState.allUsers)` so cards always show the full breakdown.
- **`renderGroupedUsers(allUsers)`** — new function:
  - Computes 4 groups from `allUsers`
  - Updates count badges
  - Renders user row cards into each list container
  - Each row card includes: name, email, role badge, approval badge, `[Approve]` or `[Approved]` button, role select, `[Details]` button — **same logic as existing table rows**

- **`renderServiceSubscriberGroups(allSubscriptions, allUsers)`** — new function:
  - Groups active subscriptions by `serviceName`
  - For each service with ≥ 1 active subscriber, creates/updates a service card in `#service-groups-grid`
  - Each subscriber row shows: name, email, status badge, start date, `[Details]` button

---

### Component 3 — JS (`dataLoaders.js`)

No changes needed — existing loaders already populate `adminState.allUsers` and `adminState.allSubscriptions`.

---

### Component 4 — JS (`userFilters.js`)

No logic changes. `applyUserFilters()` still calls `renderUsersTableData(filtered)`. The grouped cards always show the **full unfiltered** breakdown; the filter panel only affects the hidden table (existing behavior) and a new optional search highlight.

> **Design decision**: The filter panel + search bar is kept in the UI but will now also update group card results via an additional call to `renderGroupedUsers(filtered)` so the search/filter still feels connected.

---

### Component 5 — JS (`subscriptionRenderer.js`)

After `renderSubscriptions()` completes, call `renderServiceSubscriberGroups()` to refresh the service groups on the Users view.

---

### CSS (`styles.css`)

No changes to the shared stylesheet. All new styles are scoped in the `<style>` block in `admin.html`.

